LAGOS – The Federal Airports Authority of Nigeria (FAAN) has arrested more than 90 persons who engage in touting and extortion of air travelers at the Murtala Muhammed Airport (MMA), Lagos and the Nnamdi Azikiwe International Airport (NAIA), Abuja, while 89 of the suspects have been handed over to police for further investigation. FAAN said that the arrest was part of its efforts to rid the nation’s airports of authorised persons who continue to soil the name of the country in international community. A statement by Mrs. Henrietta Yakubu, the General Manager, Corporate Communication, FAAN, said that the suspects were apprehended while carrying out nefarious activities at the two airports. We’ve Put Measures In Place To Checkmate Compromise Of New… Missing £400: FAAN Debunks Pilfering Claim Against Officials The statement hinted that the touts were arrested for various acts of illegality including selling of fake Covid-19 test results, touting, unauthorised entry, trespass, illegal facilitation, forgery, loitering, theft, public nuisance and arguments, amongst others. Yakubu explained that some of those arrested were staff of Patovilki Nigeria Limited, Lakewood Services, Nigerian Aviation Handling Company (NAHCO) Plc and other airport staff. Of the total arrested, 59 were handed over to the airport police command in Abuja for prosecution, while 30 were handed over to the police force in Lagos for same. She added: ”FAAN will like to use this opportunity to warn those that do not have any legitimate business at the airports, as well as airport staff carrying out illegal duties to desist from such acts, as the Authority will not hesitate to arrest and hand over such individuals for prosecution.”